WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:10.000
Again, the areas in black are the total area covered which we obtained from the mission,

00:10.000 --> 00:18.000
and the areas in red are the pieces which we missed due to the deletion of the plane change

00:18.000 --> 00:21.000
and the day early return.

00:21.000 --> 00:27.000
This little piece down here was a oblique pass which we had planned with the pan camera.

00:27.000 --> 00:32.000
It would have taken place on Rev 72 in order to get photographs of Jacendi,

00:32.000 --> 00:37.000
which is an area of particular interest to the geology.

00:37.000 --> 00:40.000
So you can see that we did lose some data.

00:40.000 --> 00:45.000
On the other hand, we did pick up some data that we would not have gotten,

00:45.000 --> 00:54.000
and I think overall the effectiveness of the coverage was about 90% of what we had hoped for pre-mission.

00:54.000 --> 01:02.000
I really want to express the thanks of the photo team to the flight planners here

01:02.000 --> 01:07.000
and also to Ken for his operation of the cameras during the mission.

01:07.000 --> 01:13.000
I know that it was very confusing to be continually changing the flight plan

01:13.000 --> 01:18.000
and Ken probably wondered what the hell we were doing with all these on-offs and so on.

01:18.000 --> 01:30.000
But really I think we did a very effective job of recovering almost all of the data that we had planned for the mission.

01:30.000 --> 01:35.000
May I have the next slide, please?

01:35.000 --> 01:41.000
This is a diagram showing what the Apollo 15 coverage was like.

01:41.000 --> 01:45.000
This is the planned coverage for the 16 mission,

01:45.000 --> 01:49.000
and in the dotted line is the planned coverage for the 17 mission.

01:49.000 --> 01:55.000
The only reason I show this is to indicate that the areas where we did lose data, unfortunately,

01:55.000 --> 02:03.000
are in the areas that were not covered by 15 and will not be covered by 17,

02:03.000 --> 02:07.000
so that the losses, although small, were real.

02:07.000 --> 02:10.000
May I have the next slide?

02:10.000 --> 02:18.000
Ken, during the film recovery EVA, you reported that the stellar camera glare shield was hung up on the handrail.

02:18.000 --> 02:24.000
I'm not 100% clear as to exactly what that situation was.

02:24.000 --> 02:27.000
This is the stellar camera glare shield,

02:27.000 --> 02:33.000
and this is a little cover that comes down and covers that when the mapping camera is retracted.

02:33.000 --> 02:37.000
Maybe you've discussed this with the other people here at the center,

02:37.000 --> 02:44.000
but for my own information, I would like to know whether this is the cover that was hung up or this is the cover.

02:44.000 --> 02:48.000
Both of them. The shield at the forward end, that one.

02:48.000 --> 02:49.000
This one?

02:49.000 --> 02:52.000
No, the first one you looked at, yeah. That was sticking up.

02:52.000 --> 02:53.000
That was sticking up, uh-huh.

02:53.000 --> 02:57.000
Yeah, but the tip out here was mashed against the handrail.

02:57.000 --> 02:59.000
Mashed against the handrail out along here.

02:59.000 --> 03:01.000
Yeah, the rail isn't in this picture.

03:01.000 --> 03:02.000
The rail is not installed.

03:02.000 --> 03:03.000
It would have been along here.

03:03.000 --> 03:04.000
That's right.

03:04.000 --> 03:07.000
And this lip was up against it and bent back out of the way.

03:07.000 --> 03:08.000
I see.

03:08.000 --> 03:10.000
It was not in the full extend position.

03:10.000 --> 03:11.000
It looked like it was a partial extension.

03:11.000 --> 03:12.000
Uh-huh.

03:12.000 --> 03:17.000
Could you tell whether this was bent, whether this rail was bent, this extend rail?

03:17.000 --> 03:21.000
No, but I think we have a photo that will probably tell you that.

03:21.000 --> 03:22.000
I don't remember.

03:22.000 --> 03:24.000
The end of the shield was bent.

03:24.000 --> 03:25.000
Up here.

03:25.000 --> 03:26.000
No.

03:26.000 --> 03:27.000
Here.

03:27.000 --> 03:29.000
Yeah, in the next section of the accordion.

03:29.000 --> 03:30.000
The next section was bent.

03:30.000 --> 03:31.000
Yeah.

03:31.000 --> 03:33.000
Now, whether that rail itself was bent, I didn't notice.

03:33.000 --> 03:34.000
Uh-huh.

03:34.000 --> 03:35.000
Uh-huh.

03:35.000 --> 03:39.000
The implication, of course, is that if this, uh, had happened early in the mission and this

03:39.000 --> 03:45.000
shield were bent down, uh, we might get excessive light into the stellar camera and our, our background

03:45.000 --> 03:50.000
density would be, uh, low, uh, or would be higher than we expected and we might not see

03:50.000 --> 03:51.000
as many stars.

03:51.000 --> 03:58.000
Uh, the other indication of, uh, malfunction that we had, of course, was in the exposure

03:58.000 --> 04:05.000
control on the pan camera and, uh, that, uh, would indicate that, uh, the pictures away

04:05.000 --> 04:08.000
from the terminal may be overexposed.

04:08.000 --> 04:12.000
That situation is also being looked at and, again, we're going to talk about it this afternoon

04:12.000 --> 04:14.000
before we actually process the film.

04:14.000 --> 04:17.000
Uh, may I have the next slide?

04:17.000 --> 04:23.000
Uh, this is the information which I have with regard to the laser altimeter operation.

04:23.000 --> 04:29.000
Uh, the first row across here is what the nominal mission would have been and the second

04:29.000 --> 04:34.000
row is the, uh, actual results from the Apollo 16.

04:34.000 --> 04:39.000
Uh, we had planned a total of 20 hours and a few minutes of operating time.

04:39.000 --> 04:47.000
We got 14 hours and a half so that we are down about 25 percent in the total operating time.

04:47.000 --> 04:54.000
This is the total, uh, revolutions in longitude that we had planned, uh, 10.3 and we got seven

04:54.000 --> 04:59.000
and a half so again we're down about 25 percent in that regard.

04:59.000 --> 05:08.000
Uh, a total number of firings 3283 and 2106 is the actual number that, uh, was recorded.

05:08.000 --> 05:15.000
So we are down, uh, nearly 30 percent, uh, in the total number of firings.

05:15.000 --> 05:25.000
Also, the number of valid elevation, uh, readings that we got was appreciably, uh, less than the total number of firings.

05:25.000 --> 05:35.000
So that we, the actual mission in terms of altimeter observations, uh, gave us a little bit less than half of what we had actually planned.

05:35.000 --> 05:43.000
Uh, that's, that's really not as serious a, a, uh, shortfall as it sounds just from the numbers.

05:43.000 --> 05:48.000
Uh, because the readings were quite well distributed throughout the mission.

05:48.000 --> 05:56.000
Uh, the general operation that we saw on the altimeter, uh, the first several revs were completely nominal.

05:56.000 --> 05:58.000
All of the elevation readings were valid.

05:58.000 --> 06:04.000
Then it began to fall off about 75 percent, 65 percent, and down to about 60 percent,

06:04.000 --> 06:11.000
except on the last data pass on rev 62 where it was only about, uh, uh, 10 percent effective.

06:11.000 --> 06:21.000
Uh, the, uh, generally what we seem to observe is that there would be one good shot, then one bad shot, then one good, one bad,

06:21.000 --> 06:23.000
and then maybe several good ones in a row.

06:23.000 --> 06:33.000
Uh, we can talk about the reason for that, but, uh, that's more appropriately covered in the systems review tomorrow.

06:33.000 --> 06:42.000
Uh, the effect that it will have on the data is simply to give us a, a, a larger spacing between data points.

06:42.000 --> 06:49.000
So far as the, its effect on the reduction of the photography is concerned, that's absolutely inconsequential.

06:49.000 --> 06:57.000
So far as its effect on the, uh, correlation between the tracking and gravity data and the, uh, profiles,

06:57.000 --> 07:00.000
it's a little bit, uh, more of concern.

07:00.000 --> 07:04.000
Uh, they do have a little bit more smoothing to do between the data points that they got,

07:04.000 --> 07:11.000
but essentially I don't think that it really hurts us so far as the scientific return, uh, from the mission is concerned.

07:11.000 --> 07:18.000
Uh, I would like to say, uh, just a word or so about the utilization of the photography.

07:18.000 --> 07:24.000
The, it has been proceeding much more slowly than I had anticipated

07:24.000 --> 07:28.000
in reducing the pictures from Apollo 15.

07:28.000 --> 07:33.000
However, the work which is being done by the ACIC and St. Louis

07:33.000 --> 07:37.000
is indicating that the photography, photographic reduction,

07:37.000 --> 07:42.000
will provide, uh, positional coordinates of features on the lunar surface

07:42.000 --> 07:48.000
with the, uh, the accuracy of 10 to 12 meters in position and in elevation.

07:48.000 --> 07:53.000
And that seems to coincide very well with what we had predicted pre-mission.

07:53.000 --> 08:00.000
So, uh, we are quite confident that, uh, that we're getting very good information from the pictures in that regard.

08:00.000 --> 08:08.000
Uh, the tracking data, uh, generally, uh, is consistent within an orbital pass,

08:08.000 --> 08:16.000
but we do find, uh, discrepancies of, uh, up to a kilometer between adjacent photographic passes.

08:16.000 --> 08:24.000
So that the, uh, reduction of the photographs is giving us a much better tie between orbital, uh, passes

08:24.000 --> 08:28.000
than we get from the, from the tracking data, uh, itself.

08:28.000 --> 08:35.000
Uh, consequently, we do expect eventually to come up with a, an internally consistent coordinate system,

08:35.000 --> 08:40.000
reference system, figure of the moon, with an accuracy on the order of 12 to 15 meters.

08:40.000 --> 08:43.000
Uh, that's, uh, highly gratifying to me.

08:43.000 --> 08:48.000
Uh, so far as the pan-camera utilization is concerned,

08:48.000 --> 08:52.000
there have been some, uh, map compilations done.

08:52.000 --> 08:58.000
Uh, the indicated precision of those is on the order of three meters,

08:58.000 --> 09:00.000
which, again, is about what we had expected.

09:00.000 --> 09:04.000
But that is a precision and not an accuracy number because, uh,

09:04.000 --> 09:08.000
of the geometric problems with the pan-camera photography.

09:08.000 --> 09:11.000
However, so far as the resolution of the pan-camera is concerned,

09:11.000 --> 09:14.000
that has held up to just about what we had expected,

09:14.000 --> 09:20.000
uh, from one and a half to three meters at the, uh, sub-vehicle point

09:20.000 --> 09:25.000
and decreasing off to about five to six meters at the limits of the, of the film.

09:25.000 --> 09:34.000
Uh, so, so far as, uh, our indications at the moment are that the results from 16 are quite satisfactory.

09:34.000 --> 09:39.000
We do have these problems that we have to resolve in the processing of the film.

09:39.000 --> 09:44.000
And, uh, once that is done, we will be able to say exactly what we did obtain.

09:44.000 --> 09:49.000
But, again, I want to express the photo team's thanks to you particularly, Ken,

09:49.000 --> 09:55.000
for the, uh, uh, time and attention, uh, that you gave to the camera operation

09:55.000 --> 09:58.000
and the results that we have obtained.

09:58.000 --> 10:01.000
Thanks, Fred. Any questions, uh, before?

10:01.000 --> 10:04.000
Could you, do you have a plot of the, uh, altimetry?

10:04.000 --> 10:10.000
You know, last time someone had drawn up a rough hand sketch of, of the altimetry,

10:10.000 --> 10:11.000
and what, did anyone do that this time?

10:11.000 --> 10:12.000
Uh, the profiles?

10:12.000 --> 10:13.000
Yes, sir.

10:13.000 --> 10:14.000
No, I don't, Ken.

10:14.000 --> 10:18.000
I think maybe, uh, Sjogren has one of those, uh, and, uh, I don't know.

10:18.000 --> 10:19.000
Is he here?

10:19.000 --> 10:20.000
Bill?

10:20.000 --> 10:21.000
Yeah, Bill.

10:21.000 --> 10:22.000
Do you have a plot?

10:22.000 --> 10:23.000
Yeah, I thought you had one.

10:23.000 --> 10:24.000
Okay.

10:24.000 --> 10:25.000
He'll show that.

10:25.000 --> 10:28.000
Okay, and these, uh, particles that you found in the mapping camera, that,

10:28.000 --> 10:33.000
is that handfuls, or, or a couple of shavings, or?

10:33.000 --> 10:41.000
Uh, I don't know how extensive they are, they were, uh, they were enough to concern the, uh,

10:41.000 --> 10:44.000
uh, the people in the processing lab.

10:44.000 --> 10:48.000
Uh, uh, all I know, that's about all that I know about it.

10:48.000 --> 10:50.000
We're supposed to have a review of that this afternoon.

10:50.000 --> 10:54.000
Uh, it could have, uh, very serious implications, obviously.

10:54.000 --> 11:03.000
Uh, uh, one, one thing that I seem to recall from the, uh, during the mission, is that we

11:03.000 --> 11:10.000
had apparently more film left for post-TEI photography than we had anticipated.

11:10.000 --> 11:15.000
And what that could mean, of course, is that the camera was not passing film when we thought

11:15.000 --> 11:18.000
it was, and things were being chewed up pretty badly inside.

11:18.000 --> 11:24.000
So, uh, we're gonna have to look that over very carefully before we go ahead with the processing

11:24.000 --> 11:25.000
of the film.

11:25.000 --> 11:32.000
We expect the, uh, camera contractor to, uh, look at the shavings and tell us where he

11:32.000 --> 11:36.000
thinks they came from, and that may give us a better clue as to what they are, actually

11:36.000 --> 11:37.000
are.

11:37.000 --> 11:38.000
Do you have a processing schedule yet?

11:38.000 --> 11:40.000
I, I guess it's all in advance to figure out what to do next.

11:40.000 --> 11:44.000
Yeah, everything is on a hold until this afternoon, yeah, after we're meeting this afternoon.

11:44.000 --> 11:48.000
Assuming you're determined to go ahead and develop it, will it take you three or four days

11:48.000 --> 11:49.000
to process?

11:49.000 --> 11:50.000
Yeah, yeah.

11:50.000 --> 11:56.000
Uh, I think the, the anticipated schedule was to have, uh, the original film processed

11:56.000 --> 12:02.000
within this week, and all of the duplicate copies within four weeks of the distributed.

12:02.000 --> 12:05.000
Perhaps you stated, what is the accuracy of the altimeter?

12:05.000 --> 12:11.000
The, uh, least count of the altimeter is, uh, one meter.

12:11.000 --> 12:18.000
Uh, the accuracy is, uh, dependent, uh, pretty much upon the slope in the area, which is aluminum,

12:18.000 --> 12:25.000
and, uh, a little bit, uh, on the albedo in the area, which is illuminated.

12:25.000 --> 12:30.000
Uh, in general, I think it's fair to say that, uh, the reading that we get from the altimeter

12:30.000 --> 12:34.000
will be correct, uh, to within three to five meters.

12:34.000 --> 12:40.000
Have, have you figured out what to do with the pan camera for processing?

12:40.000 --> 12:44.000
Got a correction for the, for the exposure?

12:44.000 --> 12:47.000
Uh, I don't know what has been figured out.

12:47.000 --> 12:51.000
We had a group working on it last week, and they're going to give us a report right after

12:51.000 --> 12:53.000
this meeting, and we'll decide what to do.

12:53.000 --> 12:57.000
Yeah, I could, I could comment, uh, the photo lab has made their recommendation, you know,

12:57.000 --> 13:03.000
to fraud back, and, uh, they think that there will be some slight loss near the generator,

13:03.000 --> 13:10.000
if they could do that, uh, in other words, that they can handle the over exposure,

13:10.000 --> 13:15.000
but at some penalty, where we have .

13:15.000 --> 13:28.000
The situation is really that, uh, near the terminator, the pictures are underexposed anyhow,

13:28.000 --> 13:31.000
because we can't open the slit wide enough and so on.

13:31.000 --> 13:37.000
Uh, so the camera was wide open at the terminator, uh, but it was open wider than it should have been

13:37.000 --> 13:42.000
when we were away from the terminator, so that the terminator pictures are a little bit underexposed,

13:42.000 --> 13:47.000
then they become properly exposed, and after that, uh, they will be overexposed.

13:47.000 --> 13:55.000
So what we would really like, of course, is a variable, uh, processing, uh, through each photo pass,

13:55.000 --> 13:59.000
but that's probably not a feasible thing to even contemplate.

14:03.000 --> 14:05.000
Thanks, Fred.

14:05.000 --> 14:08.000
Next subject will be the particles and fields of the subsatellite,

14:08.000 --> 14:11.000
and, uh, I think Jim McCoy is going to cover that. Is he here?

14:11.000 --> 14:14.000
Ah, there he is.

14:14.000 --> 14:15.000
We got a mic right over there.

14:15.000 --> 14:16.000
Yeah.

14:16.000 --> 14:17.000
Can we add anything at all?

14:17.000 --> 14:33.000
Yeah, they'll, they'll project it up there in the back booth if you want to.

14:33.000 --> 14:34.000
Uh, Dick?

14:34.000 --> 14:35.000
Yes.

14:35.000 --> 14:36.000
Where's, where's Baldwin?

14:36.000 --> 14:39.000
Would you, could you get this projected up there?

14:39.000 --> 14:40.000
Of course.

14:40.000 --> 14:42.000
I guess I'll put the mic on.

14:42.000 --> 14:47.000
Okay, can you hear me okay?

14:47.000 --> 14:48.000
Okay.

14:48.000 --> 14:52.000
Uh, I guess, uh, quickly, the subsatellite was

14:52.000 --> 14:53.000
deployed successfully.

14:53.000 --> 14:54.000
Our spin rate was phenomenal.

14:54.000 --> 14:55.000
Uh, I guess I'll put the mic on.

14:55.000 --> 14:59.000
Uh, I guess, uh, quickly, the subsatellite was deployed successfully.

14:59.000 --> 15:14.000
Uh, our spin rate was phenomenal, about five and a ninth second, uh, spin period.

15:14.000 --> 15:21.240
Quickly, the sub-satellite was deployed successfully. Our spin rate was

15:21.240 --> 15:29.360
nominal about 5 and 8 second spin period. We want five plus or minus a couple. The

15:29.360 --> 15:34.320
attitude was good. According to preliminary indications in the sun sensor,

15:34.320 --> 15:40.220
we have a couple of degrees tip off from the ecliptic, which is well within the

15:40.220 --> 15:47.960
limits we needed. The operation of all of the electrostatic analyzers and both

15:47.960 --> 15:55.940
solid-state telescopes is good. We don't seem to have the noise problem that we

15:55.940 --> 16:02.660
had on Apollo 15 in a couple of the analyzers, and we've gotten rid of our

16:02.660 --> 16:07.060
accumulator counting error that was characteristic of 15. It's given us some

16:07.060 --> 16:16.720
problems in our data analysis now from that satellite. The quick-look results on

16:16.720 --> 16:24.800
our first magnetotail pass indicated, again, the presence of these rather unexpected,

16:24.800 --> 16:32.100
rather high fluxes of low-energy protons, which have also been seen now with a new

16:32.100 --> 16:41.280
IMP series I satellite experiment too. And on this magnetotail pass, we appear to have the

16:41.280 --> 16:49.740
remnants of a small solar event in the form of some high-energy solar cosmic ray

16:49.740 --> 16:56.580
electrons and protons around, which should prove interesting for our shadow

16:56.580 --> 17:06.240
interpretation, particularly on electric fields in the magnetotail. Beyond that, if they have those slides

17:06.240 --> 17:14.160
there, I'd like to briefly describe some of the results we got from Apollo 15, which would hope to be

17:14.160 --> 17:26.880
similar for this one. Our primary experiment was to examine particle shadow configurations in the

17:26.880 --> 17:35.700
magnetotail. That'd be while we're passing through this region back here, where we are in the Earth's magnetic field,

17:35.700 --> 17:47.880
and use that to examine the question of openness and access through the magnetotail to the magnetic field lines and

17:47.880 --> 18:00.000
ultimately to the Van Allen belts, where theory generally holds that the Van Allen radiation must somehow come in and then be trapped and

18:00.000 --> 18:14.580
accelerated. The degree of connection back here with the interplanetary field has been in quite a bit of question and briefly stated the Apollo 15 results indicate pretty

18:14.580 --> 18:29.980
clearly that at least most of the time at the latitudes where we passed through the tail, of course we only have a couple of passes, that these field lines are in fact open

18:29.980 --> 18:41.980
out here connect directly into the interplanetary field and have direct access of solar cosmopolitan particles.

18:41.980 --> 18:55.980
We have also observed the existence of a plasma sheet which is known to form in closer to the Earth to extend out to the Moon in the distance.

18:55.980 --> 19:15.980
And on at least a couple of occasions we have observed cross tail electric fields which are important to theoretical models accounting for aurora and for acceleration of particles into the radiation belts.

19:15.980 --> 19:37.980
An unexpected observation which we found interesting was 30 keV or thereabouts protons in very large numbers which we observe quite frequently back in the magnetotail and also observe outside the magnetotail in very similar fluxes.

19:37.980 --> 19:49.980
Our first feeling was that these must also be some component of the solar cosmic ray proton spectrum.

19:49.980 --> 19:59.980
their, of course, very low energy would be stopped by even the thinnest piece of material.

19:59.980 --> 20:14.980
But the numbers of them and the consistency of their flux densities make them very attractive as probably being indicative, quite indicative of the source that they come from and the mechanism bringing them.

20:14.980 --> 20:36.980
A further examination, however, of the locations where we see them and of the almost constant intensities that we see almost force us to the conclusions that they must somehow be protons from the outer Van Allen belt region here,

20:36.980 --> 21:04.980
which are somehow coming loose from the Earth's field and moving outward and then getting onto the interplanetary fields and then moving out to where we see them in perhaps an inverse process of the postulated process where we bring solar cosmic ray particles in from the Sun to populate the Van Allen belts.

21:04.980 --> 21:22.980
We were anxiously awaiting getting our data and now our computer program at Berkeley and Schaefer. We can examine this in detail. We've unfortunately been delayed in that.

21:22.980 --> 21:36.980
So, if I have the next slide, I'll show you one orbit of data from the telescopes when these very steady fluxes of protons were present.

21:36.980 --> 21:58.980
And during this period and actually for a period of a couple of orbits earlier, these fluxes were almost constant. There is some changing here. There is a very, very slight shadowing of protons, not very much at all. This is mostly an electron phenomenon.

21:58.980 --> 22:16.980
But then these particles essentially turn off as though somebody closed a valve. And this is characteristic of the way they behave. When they appear, they're suddenly there. And when they disappear, they're gone just as fast.

22:16.980 --> 22:35.980
And we're very hopeful that we'll be able to make some sense out of what turns these things on and off and determine where they're coming from and what the mechanism is, presumably now in the magnetosphere.

22:35.980 --> 22:47.980
Okay, I think I'll just throw it open to any questions now.

22:47.980 --> 22:48.980
Okay.

22:48.980 --> 22:52.980
What is the lifetime estimate of the 16th?

22:52.980 --> 22:56.980
I wish you hadn't brought that up.

22:56.980 --> 22:59.980
The next speaker will get that for us.

22:59.980 --> 23:07.980
We had been very hopeful of getting another dozen or a couple of dozen magnetosphere passes out of this satellite since it works so beautifully.

23:07.980 --> 23:12.980
I think we're going to cover that.

23:12.980 --> 23:15.980
Chris said it was going to stay up there forever, so it better.

23:15.980 --> 23:22.980
If it doesn't crash, we also will.

23:22.980 --> 23:26.980
Then the world's going to come to an end pretty shortly, I'm over.

23:26.980 --> 23:27.980
We'll see.

23:27.980 --> 23:30.980
Any questions about particles and fuels?

23:30.980 --> 23:33.980
Okay, let's continue on with subsatellite and get on the planet.

23:33.980 --> 23:34.980
We didn't say anything about it.

23:34.980 --> 23:38.980
I assume that our satellite is sending out good data.

23:38.980 --> 23:41.980
Is batteries charging okay and everything?

23:41.980 --> 23:45.980
It's not running into the problem that the 15 guys had?

23:45.980 --> 23:47.980
Or was that normal for the...

23:47.980 --> 23:50.980
It seems to be a little bit better at battery charging.

23:50.980 --> 23:51.980
Yeah.

23:51.980 --> 23:52.980
The machine is working.

23:52.980 --> 23:54.980
Okay, and all the detectors are operating?

23:54.980 --> 23:55.980
Yeah.

23:55.980 --> 23:57.980
As far as we know, yeah.

23:57.980 --> 23:59.980
It's just that it's got a short lifetime.

23:59.980 --> 24:00.980
Okay, let's see.

24:00.980 --> 24:06.980
I think Larry Sharp is going to take Coleman's place, right?

24:06.980 --> 24:07.980
Okay.

24:07.980 --> 24:08.980
Magnetometer.

24:08.980 --> 24:12.980
The objectives of the magnetometer experiment are essentially three-fold.

24:12.980 --> 24:17.980
First is to measure and map the remnant magnetism on the lunar surface.

24:17.980 --> 24:21.980
Second is to map the electrical conductivity of the lunar interior.

24:21.980 --> 24:28.980
Finally, study the various aspects of the Moon's interaction with the fields and particles in its environment.

24:28.980 --> 24:37.980
The wide scope of these objectives is made possible by the geometry of the Moon's orbit as it passes through three fundamentally different regions of space.

24:37.980 --> 24:45.980
For example, to get the spatial variations of remnant magnetism on the lunar surface, one must be in the geomagnetic tail,

24:45.980 --> 24:50.980
where the temporal variations are almost absent in the magnetic field.

24:50.980 --> 24:52.980
Very steady situation.

24:52.980 --> 25:03.980
The initial orbit of the subsatellite was somewhat lower than Apollo 15 in the inclination of about 11 degrees instead of 28.

25:03.980 --> 25:16.980
And I'd like to show you the predictions of the orbit.

25:16.980 --> 25:17.980
Right over that side.

25:17.980 --> 25:18.980
On the back side.

25:18.980 --> 25:19.980
Back side over.

25:19.980 --> 25:20.980
Ha, Ha, Ha.

25:22.980 --> 25:41.980
Okay, we've plotted days past deployment.

25:41.980 --> 25:43.980
Versus the parallel altitude.

25:43.980 --> 25:44.980
Okay.

25:44.980 --> 25:50.760
We started out here in pretty good shape, about 97 kilometers or 97 by 123, I guess.

25:51.400 --> 25:58.580
And the prediction was a very rapid drop down to 30-some, back up in good shape.

25:59.100 --> 26:08.780
No real trouble until, here's the ground line, until about 200 days when the probability was 50-50 of a crash.

26:08.780 --> 26:10.380
Here are the error bars here.

26:10.800 --> 26:15.440
You can say the probability was maybe one chance in 10 of a crash here and maybe one chance in 5.

26:15.860 --> 26:16.980
We've updated this plot.

26:29.820 --> 26:31.780
And the odds have changed considerably.

26:32.740 --> 26:33.940
This was the prediction.

26:34.300 --> 26:38.180
Notice the timescale has been expanded greatly.

26:38.180 --> 26:39.840
These are hours now instead of days.

26:40.760 --> 26:49.100
Here was the initial prediction at 37 kilometers, and here are the actual data points.

26:49.600 --> 26:52.180
This one was taken this morning, around in here.

26:52.880 --> 26:56.800
And if you can extrapolate by eye, it looks like we have about four days left.

26:58.120 --> 27:02.280
I guess Bill Sogren's taking 50-50 odds that it'll crash if anyone's in the betting mood.

27:02.900 --> 27:05.860
It's possible that we'll skim the surface and come back out.

27:05.860 --> 27:14.000
But even if we make it through this one, that next dip is going to probably finish us off, which is most unfortunate.

27:14.000 --> 27:21.280
Out of curiosity, it might be out of your field, but how come our prediction didn't match the actuality?

27:21.280 --> 27:22.280
I mean, we...

27:22.280 --> 27:33.140
We don't know the gravity field that well, and that's the business of this subsatellite initially to come to the gravity field.

27:33.200 --> 27:34.320
You're going to come to that field, I think.

27:35.060 --> 27:35.400
Right.

27:35.400 --> 27:46.800
And we've been screaming like that about these paths that don't go long out here at MSC to try to drive that point home so many times,

27:46.860 --> 27:48.900
and I think we're really seeing it come.

27:50.200 --> 27:54.440
Man, it just goes to show you can't redo six months of planning in two days.

27:54.440 --> 28:03.940
Well, in any event, we have one month's worth of good data, which will add to our Apollo 15 results.

28:04.740 --> 28:09.860
And to get some idea of what we're doing with this data, I'd like to show the first slide,

28:09.860 --> 28:19.020
which represents an average of 17 different orbits taken when the moon was in the Earth's magnetotail.

28:20.160 --> 28:29.720
And we've plotted the moon's longitude along the horizontal and the magnetic field in gammas along the vertical.

28:30.120 --> 28:33.140
These numbers are representative of the Earth's tail field.

28:33.140 --> 28:40.780
And, of course, if you subtract out an average value, this residual would represent the lunar surface field.

28:41.560 --> 28:49.300
And, of course, the big result is this really huge magnetic dip going over the Vondegraaff crater

28:49.300 --> 28:51.020
or a region right near the Vondegraaff crater.

28:52.060 --> 28:58.640
Also, the other initial result we got out of 15 data was that most of the dips in the magnetic field

28:58.640 --> 29:05.940
would seem to be clearly associated with craters lying within a few degrees of the ground track defined by the orbit of the subsatellite.

29:06.600 --> 29:13.600
We've numbered the seven most obvious local minima and named five of them with associated craters.

29:14.860 --> 29:21.020
Now, initial results from Apollo 16 show the same type of structure, although we don't see anything as big as Vondegraaff.

29:21.120 --> 29:23.160
We see we do go over Korolev again.

29:23.160 --> 29:25.860
That's where the orbits intersect when we're in the tail.

29:25.860 --> 29:31.660
And we see a few other Hertzsprung and Pavlov-type bumps.

29:32.800 --> 29:38.880
One is with a little tiny crater called Stein and one near Mendelev.

29:40.600 --> 29:43.800
Now, if you repeat this procedure several times with different lunations,

29:44.020 --> 29:49.680
say you cover different tracks over the moon, and this allows a contour map to be made.

29:49.680 --> 29:59.860
So if I could have the next slide, this shows the ground track from where we found the anomaly.

29:59.960 --> 30:01.940
Here was one over Hertzsprung, Korolev.

30:02.800 --> 30:03.740
Here's Vondegraaff.

30:03.800 --> 30:08.240
You can see we went right close to the northern border, Pavlov, and one over Milne.

30:08.820 --> 30:12.440
So it was a pretty good one-to-one correspondence with large craters.

30:12.440 --> 30:19.500
The initial 11 orbit, of course, is much near the equator.

30:19.660 --> 30:21.860
The inclination goes up to plus or minus 11.

30:22.540 --> 30:27.740
So we saw one over Korolev, and Stein crater is located right about here.

30:27.820 --> 30:28.560
It's not too big.

30:29.420 --> 30:32.860
The next map shows a compilation of a lot of these linear profiles.

30:33.600 --> 30:34.280
Next slide.

30:34.560 --> 30:36.620
Into a contour map.

30:36.620 --> 30:40.180
It's a little hard to read the contours.

30:41.680 --> 30:47.680
You can see this big black blotch here is a result of contours stacked on top of each other

30:47.680 --> 30:50.380
near this Vondegraaff anomaly.

30:51.040 --> 30:55.140
You can see the numbers are hard to make out.

30:55.220 --> 30:59.460
You can see the structure over Korolev, a hint of some structure over Hertzsprung,

30:59.460 --> 31:07.240
and the southern sea over here is actually an enhancement, sticking out of the moon, so to speak.

31:07.380 --> 31:09.520
You can see Milne shows a definite structure.

31:10.320 --> 31:15.640
Now, the Apollo 16 results should enable us to expand this map.

31:15.740 --> 31:20.340
We'll get better resolutions throughout this area and be able to extend it along in here.

31:20.420 --> 31:22.120
We'll probably still have a gap down in this region.

31:22.520 --> 31:25.720
Harry, can you give us an idea of the gradient you're measuring there?

31:25.860 --> 31:26.360
Oh, yes.

31:26.620 --> 31:26.940
Okay.

31:26.940 --> 31:31.320
The numbers presented in the chart, if you can see them,

31:31.420 --> 31:35.700
are measured in tenths of gamma at an altitude of 100 kilometers.

31:36.460 --> 31:40.720
So, for example, a good representative value is about 30,

31:41.240 --> 31:44.400
and the zero we've arbitrarily chosen at the bottom of the Vondegraaff dip,

31:44.500 --> 31:48.600
since this is the lowest value of magnetism we observe.

31:48.740 --> 31:51.100
We just call it zero and scale everything relative to it.

31:51.100 --> 31:58.160
So, if you're at 100 kilometers, you'll see a three gamma dip going over Vondegraaff on the average.

31:58.160 --> 32:00.960
Oh, we were fortunate.

32:02.380 --> 32:03.800
Also, the near side of the moon.

32:04.220 --> 32:07.720
Does the gravity profile have any, can you correlate?

32:07.720 --> 32:12.960
I've looked at the gravity profile, and it doesn't seem to correlate at all.

32:14.400 --> 32:14.840
We don't.

32:14.900 --> 32:19.220
Actually, the laser data correlates better with, you don't, there's no gravity on the back side, okay,

32:19.260 --> 32:20.000
but on the front side.

32:20.080 --> 32:20.360
I understand.

32:20.360 --> 32:24.760
It correlates pretty well with the laser data,

32:24.800 --> 32:27.860
which shows a great big hole here in the back side of the moon around Vondegraaff,

32:27.960 --> 32:28.920
and that's where we get our big hole,

32:29.040 --> 32:33.520
but I can't see any scientific justification for connecting the two results.

32:34.060 --> 32:36.460
I will add, let's remind you, the gamma ray.

32:36.840 --> 32:37.480
Yes, that's true.

32:37.480 --> 32:39.360
The secondary peak is also in Vondegraaff.

32:39.500 --> 32:40.560
I don't know what it means.

32:41.040 --> 32:42.520
It could be an alien star base or something.

32:43.480 --> 32:46.620
Anyway, the next slide shows the front side of the moon,

32:46.620 --> 32:51.660
and it's upside down.

32:52.620 --> 32:55.660
The thing to contrast is the much smoother nature of the,

32:55.920 --> 32:59.220
could we do a 180 on the slide, please?

33:05.700 --> 33:06.460
Can you hear me?

33:07.120 --> 33:08.720
Could we have a, turn the slide around, please?

33:11.200 --> 33:12.300
Oh, he's on a coffee break.

33:12.520 --> 33:13.040
Okay, here you go.

33:13.040 --> 33:18.320
Anyway, the front side of the moon is much, much smoother than the back side.

33:19.060 --> 33:24.140
The variations are, oh, an order of a factor of 10 smooth.

33:24.220 --> 33:25.720
We don't see very much structure at all.

33:26.260 --> 33:28.360
It's very hard to even draw contours.

33:28.360 --> 33:38.920
Can you sort out the differences in that and the effects of running through the,

33:38.920 --> 33:41.540
the Earth's magnetic field effects?

33:42.200 --> 33:46.800
Since you're, the front side is always close to the Earth,

33:46.880 --> 33:47.860
can you sort out,

33:49.560 --> 33:53.900
are we really measuring magnetic variations on the back side,

33:54.060 --> 33:55.420
caused by being on the back side,

33:55.420 --> 33:57.420
not due to our measuring environment?

33:57.980 --> 33:58.360
Oh, right.

33:58.480 --> 34:00.580
The Earth's tail field is very, very constant

34:00.580 --> 34:01.860
when you're in the,

34:01.860 --> 34:04.980
a good second, when you're away from the neutral sheet,

34:05.200 --> 34:06.480
and that's where all this data is taken.

34:06.480 --> 34:11.100
Well, I guess we never got the front slide complete.

34:12.420 --> 34:15.300
Okay, this is a blow-up of the Van de Graaff region

34:15.300 --> 34:19.960
in an attempt to pinpoint the exact source of this large anomaly.

34:20.540 --> 34:23.020
We kind of suspected it was over the crater itself,

34:23.920 --> 34:26.560
since we had always put forth a theory

34:26.560 --> 34:28.280
that what we were actually observing in these dips

34:28.280 --> 34:30.960
was some sort of a meteorite impact

34:30.960 --> 34:34.180
that caused a rather uniformly magnetized crust

34:34.180 --> 34:35.360
that suddenly have holes in it,

34:35.520 --> 34:37.020
and we're seeing the equivalent dipole

34:37.020 --> 34:39.940
of what was left over,

34:40.000 --> 34:41.600
and this kind of shoots holes in the theory.

34:41.720 --> 34:44.440
We see a, this is the BX component,

34:44.540 --> 34:45.500
which is the radial component,

34:45.800 --> 34:48.700
and a plus number indicates a value sticking into the moon.

34:49.700 --> 34:54.380
So you see this rather large hole here,

34:54.460 --> 34:56.240
magnetically, in between two craters,

34:56.240 --> 35:03.520
and if you look at various models of double dipoles and stuff,

35:03.560 --> 35:04.620
it just doesn't quite fit.

35:04.620 --> 35:07.600
The other components, B sub Y and B sub Z,

35:07.800 --> 35:10.960
show that it can't be one of these angling dipoles from the crater.

35:13.440 --> 35:16.280
And presently, we're now conducting the same sort of studies

35:16.280 --> 35:18.420
over the rest of the anomalies to see if it checks out.

35:18.540 --> 35:21.660
I just, just yesterday, completed the one over Korolev,

35:21.660 --> 35:24.240
and that one is right in the middle of the crater,

35:24.480 --> 35:28.860
which is promising for the Shakti magnetization theory.

35:33.740 --> 35:35.980
How much validity do we have in the ground track data?

35:40.540 --> 35:44.600
How much validity do we have in the ephemers?

35:45.020 --> 35:47.760
I understand there's no chance that we could be off by...

35:47.760 --> 35:48.800
Oh, never, anything like that.

35:48.840 --> 35:50.980
It might be off a kilometer or two, like I said.

35:51.660 --> 35:56.040
But now you're talking about the final reading there,

35:56.120 --> 35:57.400
that's 9 or 10 kilometers.

35:59.760 --> 36:01.280
So it doesn't seem much chance.

36:03.700 --> 36:05.040
We'll get maybe one more.

36:05.160 --> 36:07.560
As the subsatellite comes crashing down to the moon,

36:07.640 --> 36:10.480
the last 10 kilometers should give us a good swath of data,

36:10.940 --> 36:14.360
which will give us another high-resolution plot like this.

36:15.980 --> 36:18.160
Other than that, we're kind of out of luck.

36:18.160 --> 36:21.060
Okay.

36:22.620 --> 36:23.440
Okay, thank you.

36:24.540 --> 36:24.900
Question?

36:26.900 --> 36:27.260
Okay.

36:29.680 --> 36:30.880
There's the front side of the moon.

36:31.660 --> 36:34.880
Okay, and our coverage from Apollo 11 will extend.

36:35.620 --> 36:37.360
Yeah, I believe this is the equator across here.

36:37.360 --> 36:42.920
Oh, I'm sorry.

36:43.040 --> 36:44.760
Okay, this is zero degrees.

36:45.700 --> 36:48.340
Okay, and we go from zero to 90 east to 90 west.

36:48.420 --> 36:48.940
It's the terminator.

36:49.360 --> 36:50.560
This is the southern sea region,

36:50.640 --> 36:53.940
which is about the only distinctive feature on the front side, per se,

36:54.000 --> 36:55.220
and even that's on the terminator.

36:55.700 --> 36:59.740
And again, these are relatively high values of magnetic fields sticking out of the moon.

36:59.740 --> 37:04.060
So you might say that the southern sea is a highly magnetized region.

37:05.520 --> 37:08.480
Notice the 16th site is out of our coverage,

37:08.820 --> 37:11.580
as were all the Apollo landing sites.

37:12.200 --> 37:16.280
You have about three gamma delta on the back side.

37:16.400 --> 37:17.820
What are we seeing on the front side?

37:18.700 --> 37:22.220
Well, most of these values are about 30, 28, 27,

37:22.480 --> 37:25.780
which means they're all three gamma higher than zero at Vandegraaff.

37:25.780 --> 37:31.100
So I would say the maximum plus or minus is about a half a gamma on the whole front side.

37:31.980 --> 37:34.620
Why do you remember these elongate parallel to the track?

37:36.820 --> 37:40.500
This is a function of not having quite enough data.

37:41.000 --> 37:43.480
Instead of making physical-looking contours,

37:43.620 --> 37:45.540
we drew actual contours with the data.

37:45.660 --> 37:48.220
And obviously, if there's a little bit of offset from one orbit to the next,

37:48.640 --> 37:50.860
it's going to result in elongated contours.

37:50.860 --> 37:56.180
If we fixed this up and made some intelligent-looking guesses,

37:56.940 --> 37:58.240
they would be much more circular.

37:59.400 --> 38:05.880
Do you have a data on the Apollo 12 and the 15th and the 16th surface?

38:07.080 --> 38:09.640
Yes, with 12, 14, 15, yes.

38:09.700 --> 38:13.420
How do you compare it with the information of the surface?

38:13.640 --> 38:18.840
Well, you see, the surface data deals with much smaller scale-sized phenomena.

38:18.840 --> 38:22.020
And so there's really no one-to-one correlation.

38:22.620 --> 38:24.840
I suppose that the...

38:25.680 --> 38:27.840
Well, the Apollo 12 site is supposed to be...

38:28.560 --> 38:35.900
Well, if we could be sure that over a region of 100 kilometers

38:35.900 --> 38:39.840
that the average field was 38 gamma, which no one would bet on,

38:40.480 --> 38:44.920
then we could make some interesting predictions about other places on the moon.

38:44.920 --> 38:49.380
But I suspect if you went down to Apollo 12 and went 100 meters away,

38:49.440 --> 38:51.660
you'd find a much different value of a magnetic field.

38:52.020 --> 38:52.780
We know it's the case.

38:52.820 --> 38:53.800
Look at Apollo 14.

38:54.420 --> 38:57.480
They went one kilometer, and they went from 43 gamma to 103 gamma.

38:58.160 --> 39:02.660
So who's to say what's a representative value for the magnetic field in a given area?

39:03.700 --> 39:04.700
How about 15?

39:04.700 --> 39:11.180
Apollo 15, they saw a steady field of 6 plus or minus 4 gamma, which is essentially zero.

39:11.700 --> 39:16.620
But there again, you know, behind the next boulder, probably would be 100 gamma, probably, you know.

39:18.880 --> 39:21.460
And the results on 16, I thought, were tremendous.

39:21.660 --> 39:24.020
The tremendous gradients they got between one place and another.

39:24.020 --> 39:32.140
But that 313 gamma field really surprised me as far as getting a value that large.

39:34.700 --> 39:35.920
Yes, question there.

39:36.000 --> 39:40.480
Have you seen any distinctive features about the correlate,

39:40.620 --> 39:44.240
which might make the distinction that it was, say, a hard spot

39:44.240 --> 39:53.140
that it would have been near the surface and the necessary soil covering,

39:53.360 --> 39:56.820
which would change the surface temperature at that point,

39:56.920 --> 39:58.060
which would then change the temperature?

39:59.600 --> 40:02.140
No, I'm not a geologist type.

40:03.740 --> 40:05.480
Well, I already know about the surface.

40:05.480 --> 40:10.480
That would change the temperature.

40:10.480 --> 40:15.420
It would seem to me that the younger a crater was,

40:15.480 --> 40:19.260
the more chance it would have to produce a good, clean-cut signature

40:19.260 --> 40:22.700
on the magnetic field data.

40:23.980 --> 40:26.880
For example, Van de Graaff itself looks like a fairly young crater

40:26.880 --> 40:30.500
because there's very few secondary craters in the bottom of it.

40:30.500 --> 40:35.940
So it looks fairly young, whereas things like Hertzsprung seem to be fairly old.

40:36.140 --> 40:38.400
They're well-blotched with secondary craters.

40:40.480 --> 40:44.580
What is the distance from the center of Van de Graaff to the center of the anomaly?

40:45.160 --> 40:47.240
It's 88 kilometers from the northern rim.

40:48.800 --> 40:53.020
So from the center of Van de Graaff, it's about 130, 140 kilometers.

40:57.220 --> 40:58.220
Any other questions?

40:59.420 --> 41:00.460
Okay, thank you, Larry.

41:00.880 --> 41:03.460
And, yeah, got a question?

41:03.660 --> 41:03.800
No.

41:04.660 --> 41:06.660
Last subject will be the transponder.

41:07.540 --> 41:08.020
Bill Sogren.

41:08.020 --> 41:38.000
This is a gravity experiment.

41:38.000 --> 41:45.280
And we monitor the gravity by just monitoring the velocity of the spacecraft

41:45.280 --> 41:49.300
or the LEM or the subsatellite.

41:50.140 --> 41:54.700
Of course, on this particular mission, we lost our LEM data on impact

41:54.700 --> 41:55.540
because it started tumbling.

41:56.100 --> 41:58.100
And so that data was lost.

41:58.200 --> 42:03.000
We do, however, have the CSM in the low-altitude orbit,

42:03.000 --> 42:06.680
which is very interesting data.

42:06.680 --> 42:29.300
Here's the orbital track.

42:30.100 --> 42:32.740
And hopefully I can get this aligned.

42:35.380 --> 42:36.440
About like that.

42:37.140 --> 42:43.480
This profile just below it is the gravity anomaly that was detected.

42:43.480 --> 42:50.060
This line right here represents zero gravity central isostatic equilibrium.

42:50.760 --> 42:55.960
And anything below it, of course, that would be negative gravity deviations.

42:55.960 --> 43:02.340
Here we are, Ptolemaeus, going essentially over the center with the track.

43:02.400 --> 43:06.380
And we can see the large negative anomaly again, almost 100 milligals.

43:06.380 --> 43:13.180
Here we see some highland material where we have a positive.

43:13.180 --> 43:18.300
Then we drop down into a relative low in between these two old craters,

43:18.440 --> 43:19.800
the Parkus and Albatagnius.

43:19.800 --> 43:22.300
And then a high in here.

43:23.140 --> 43:26.980
At this point, this is the Descartes landing site.

43:27.040 --> 43:30.800
And we're actually at about a 50 milligal negative anomaly in that region.

43:31.740 --> 43:36.040
There's some nice correlations here with the laser altimetry measurements.

43:36.140 --> 43:39.000
I'll show them in the next profile.

43:39.360 --> 43:40.480
But this is continuous.

43:40.580 --> 43:42.200
I've just taken one small section here.

43:42.200 --> 43:45.660
We have this thing from limb to limb.

43:45.800 --> 43:49.480
So about 110 longitude plus to 110 minus.

43:50.480 --> 43:54.580
And essentially, three revs.

43:54.580 --> 43:58.780
From rev 3 through rev 11.

43:59.060 --> 44:00.060
That's eight revs.

44:00.360 --> 44:03.000
Eight revs of data that are pretty good.

44:03.240 --> 44:05.860
And then they started their station keeping.

44:06.240 --> 44:08.560
And data kind of got garbaged up a lot.

44:08.780 --> 44:10.320
All the maneuvering was going on.

44:12.200 --> 44:17.540
Let me point out one kind of interesting thing here.

44:19.040 --> 44:23.280
Notice that Ptolemaeus here has an anomaly much lower than Nubium.

44:23.700 --> 44:25.920
Although Nubium, which is this region right in here,

44:25.980 --> 44:31.160
this Marinubium right in here, is still at about minus 50 milligals.

44:31.160 --> 44:43.840
Here's an altimeter profile.

44:45.840 --> 44:50.240
And going right to the Nubium Ptolemaeus region again,

44:50.280 --> 44:54.840
we see that Nubium elevation here is some, by the way,

44:54.840 --> 44:58.720
the scale here is two kilometers per heavy line.

44:59.060 --> 45:01.600
So we've dropped down here almost two kilometers

45:01.600 --> 45:04.320
from the floor of Ptolemaeus to the floor of Nubium.

45:05.000 --> 45:09.680
Yet the gravity anomaly is just the opposite.

45:09.940 --> 45:15.180
The Ptolemaeus is some 50 milligals lower than the Nubium region.

45:15.180 --> 45:19.580
And another interesting point is, Fred, on these ACIC maps,

45:20.380 --> 45:23.760
Nubium is shown a kilometer higher than Ptolemaeus.

45:24.840 --> 45:27.360
And here we are two kilometers lower.

45:27.440 --> 45:29.220
So we're talking about three kilometers discrepancy

45:29.220 --> 45:31.300
in just that little area right there.

45:31.380 --> 45:34.160
So I think some of these guys were talking about the right thing

45:34.160 --> 45:37.120
when they said we really didn't know the altitudes too well.

45:37.120 --> 45:40.180
I think that shows up quite dramatically

45:40.180 --> 45:45.300
when you look at the low sun angle view

45:45.300 --> 45:46.420
as you approach the Terminator,

45:46.580 --> 45:49.860
the things that were in Nubium didn't show up

45:49.860 --> 45:53.200
until significantly after we anticipated.

45:53.460 --> 45:55.440
We missed our times on those things a great deal,

45:55.540 --> 45:56.520
and that could only be called

45:56.520 --> 45:59.540
by having a discrepancy in our relative heights.

45:59.820 --> 45:59.980
Yeah.

46:00.240 --> 46:02.320
This is not just, this is Rev. 28.

46:02.320 --> 46:06.460
We've looked at, there are five real good tracking,

46:06.780 --> 46:08.340
laser tracking passes over this region,

46:08.440 --> 46:09.600
and we've looked at three of them,

46:09.960 --> 46:13.320
and all three show the same consistency of the drop there.

46:13.680 --> 46:14.720
Other interesting thing here,

46:15.220 --> 46:18.520
Procolorum, Tranquilitatis, Frecunditatis,

46:18.560 --> 46:20.300
they all seem to be about on the same level.

46:21.180 --> 46:24.700
Smithii, again, being a low, about four and a half kilometers,

46:24.780 --> 46:27.760
that was the same thing on Apollo 15 when we passed over it.

46:28.120 --> 46:29.900
It was some four and a half kilometers below,

46:30.400 --> 46:31.480
that's mean radius here.

46:31.480 --> 46:39.580
And we're still referencing this to a 1738, well, 0.1 radius off the CG.

46:40.840 --> 46:46.820
If you take this stuff and start fitting it to an optical center

46:46.820 --> 46:49.080
with a CG offset,

46:49.840 --> 46:53.200
that you do indeed get the two-kilometer shift again

46:53.200 --> 46:56.400
of the CG being closer to the Earth by some two kilometers.

46:57.260 --> 47:00.900
Let's say that tranquility is about two and a half kilometers

47:00.900 --> 47:01.860
lower than Descartes.

47:02.860 --> 47:03.560
That's right.

47:04.020 --> 47:05.660
Yeah, here's the landing site right in here.

47:06.140 --> 47:09.040
And this is, we had a negative gravity anomaly in here.

47:09.160 --> 47:10.920
Well, kind of according to this,

47:11.000 --> 47:12.740
maybe that's the situation,

47:12.860 --> 47:15.000
because it looks like a topographic lobe.

47:15.000 --> 47:28.740
This is the backside.

47:28.740 --> 47:32.940
We had some, these are the limbs where the data was missing.

47:32.940 --> 47:36.100
These are taken from those, this data is taken from that Thrift printout

47:36.100 --> 47:39.040
that we get in real time, and there's gaps in the data.

47:39.040 --> 47:43.660
These will be filled in once they get the station tapes delivered.

47:44.120 --> 47:46.800
But we can see the crater Hertz sprung here very evidently

47:46.800 --> 47:48.540
with the central peak or something in it.

47:49.220 --> 47:55.100
You don't have any data in that 120-degree region, huh?

47:55.420 --> 47:56.000
Not now.

47:56.000 --> 47:59.860
We should have it next week or so, whenever they get the tapes here and the goose.

48:03.700 --> 48:08.460
One of the things that, well, on Apollo 15, there was a definite,

48:08.760 --> 48:09.840
well, centered about 180.

48:10.540 --> 48:14.080
There was a definite big trough in here

48:14.080 --> 48:16.300
which went down about some four and a half kilometers.

48:16.520 --> 48:17.640
It was very jagged.

48:18.280 --> 48:19.700
But it was centered just about here.

48:19.860 --> 48:22.940
And on Apollo 16 now, we do not really see that.

48:22.940 --> 48:27.380
We see this highland material here, which we had on 15.

48:27.620 --> 48:34.000
That started about in here and showed a marked high region in there.

48:34.420 --> 48:37.360
And this is holding on 16 also.

48:37.520 --> 48:42.840
So this is kind of consistent with 15.

48:44.480 --> 48:48.220
Here's another, this is orbit 38 on the backside.

48:48.220 --> 48:51.640
I'll just kind of lay it there to show you some of the consistency.

48:52.940 --> 48:55.320
This is 10 orbits later.

48:56.600 --> 48:58.260
The profile is almost there.

48:58.320 --> 48:58.920
Smith, the eye.

48:59.760 --> 49:01.560
Oh, here we have some data in that.

49:02.540 --> 49:03.660
So there's your data.

49:05.400 --> 49:05.720
Okay.

49:06.620 --> 49:07.000
I don't know.

49:07.220 --> 49:08.320
Were you looking for something particular?

49:08.580 --> 49:10.560
Yeah, I was looking for something around 105.

49:10.560 --> 49:11.860
105.

49:11.860 --> 49:12.180
105.

49:19.660 --> 49:20.500
Probably not particular.

49:20.860 --> 49:21.060
Nothing.

49:21.760 --> 49:22.120
Okay.

49:22.120 --> 49:29.160
I do have some data on the sub-satellite from Apollo 15,

49:29.280 --> 49:31.120
but I don't know if that's the time to really show here.

49:31.160 --> 49:32.940
I think I've shown enough stuff on 16, huh?

49:33.560 --> 49:35.380
Yeah, well, I'd like to stick to 16.

49:35.560 --> 49:39.060
Any of the problems we have or any of the data that we got for the crew.

49:39.060 --> 49:43.500
Well, I'm very happy with all the data we've gotten on 16,

49:43.760 --> 49:49.800
and the sub-satellite on 16, like Larry mentioned just before me,

49:50.520 --> 49:51.300
looks pretty grim.

49:51.340 --> 49:56.000
Although there was an OD solution just run out about an hour ago

49:56.000 --> 50:06.860
where the last state vector was used as the position for running out the lifetime program.

50:07.480 --> 50:11.820
And the lifetime program, if we believe that 15-8 model that we had used initially back there

50:11.820 --> 50:13.680
when we ejected that thing,

50:14.080 --> 50:16.740
it says that this thing should come back up.

50:16.880 --> 50:18.240
It still says it's not going to crash.

50:18.240 --> 50:23.120
But this will be a very interesting thing to watch the next couple of days, I can say.

50:23.120 --> 50:23.220
Right.

50:24.120 --> 50:24.780
That's all right.

50:24.860 --> 50:26.820
We own the seismometers up and ready.

50:27.140 --> 50:27.780
Well, it's 50.

50:30.480 --> 50:32.780
I asked Kovach about that,

50:32.880 --> 50:35.180
and I don't know whether he can speak for length or not,

50:35.180 --> 50:38.420
but I told him it's 50 pounds,

50:38.540 --> 50:40.680
and whether he can actually see an impact of 50 pounds,

50:41.000 --> 50:42.460
I think that's all it weighs.

50:43.820 --> 50:44.940
The central station.

50:48.800 --> 50:49.340
Let's see.

50:49.380 --> 50:54.380
It should hit about maybe some 20 or 30 degrees west longitude

50:54.380 --> 50:56.580
and 5 or 6 degrees north.

50:56.620 --> 50:57.300
Is that right, Dick?

50:58.200 --> 50:59.180
Something like that.

50:59.860 --> 51:02.780
About 5 or 6 north latitude and about 30 west.

51:03.620 --> 51:05.860
That's what it looks like, that linear extrapolation.

51:06.060 --> 51:06.220
Okay.

51:10.440 --> 51:11.260
Thank you, Bill.

51:12.440 --> 51:13.800
Thank you, gentlemen, for attending.

51:14.260 --> 51:16.460
This concludes our scientific debrief,

51:17.160 --> 51:20.640
and I'd like to thank the crew for giving their time up to come on over

51:20.640 --> 51:24.040
to give us some information and also learn some things of what happened.

51:24.400 --> 51:24.680
Okay.

51:24.980 --> 51:26.880
Let me say something for the crew.

51:27.300 --> 51:31.700
I want to commend Ken for the way that he operated the sim bay.

51:31.880 --> 51:34.920
I don't think you'll ever find a guy who's either more interested in it

51:34.920 --> 51:38.580
or more aware of what the operational problems were

51:38.580 --> 51:40.360
and who could do a better job.

51:41.380 --> 51:44.660
He really did an outstanding job, and I think he's well done.

51:44.740 --> 51:48.180
The other thing I'd like to say is since I've been on this program,

51:48.320 --> 51:52.820
I've been continually impressed with the importance of what we're doing

51:52.820 --> 51:56.660
in our support of you guys.

51:56.660 --> 51:59.580
These experiments, they look way out right now,

52:00.160 --> 52:03.540
and they're difficult for the man in the street to relate to,

52:03.540 --> 52:07.820
but my feeling is from some of the things I've seen here

52:07.820 --> 52:12.980
and from the thrust of science and technology in this country

52:12.980 --> 52:17.300
that in our lifetime, and I won't want to say when,

52:17.360 --> 52:21.800
but I imagine it's going to be a damn sight sooner than anybody even here in this room can imagine,

52:21.800 --> 52:26.260
there are going to be practical applications of some of these discoveries that have been made

52:26.260 --> 52:30.280
that will affect every one of us, and I think you're to be congratulated.

52:30.380 --> 52:34.020
The other thing is that I get out of all this that I think the United States ought to be spending

52:34.020 --> 52:38.620
two to three times the amount of money that we are spending on basic research and development

52:38.620 --> 52:40.200
and applied research and development,

52:40.200 --> 52:45.020
and I think that if you really look at the big picture of our energy requirements

52:45.020 --> 52:50.620
for clean energy in the future in order to improve the life of human beings on this planet,

52:50.740 --> 52:52.180
we ought to do that and get on with it.

52:52.820 --> 52:53.220
Thank you.

52:58.420 --> 53:02.220
During the next couple of months,

53:02.480 --> 53:07.120
we'll probably have an opportunity to talk to a lot of people

53:07.120 --> 53:10.280
that help to have some influence

53:10.280 --> 53:13.260
or shape the pattern of our program and related programs,

53:13.820 --> 53:17.820
and I would appreciate it very much.

53:17.940 --> 53:19.780
I'm sure we all could use the data.

53:20.120 --> 53:23.740
As you find out things, we realize that you have preliminary data today,

53:23.800 --> 53:27.740
and a lot of the things are only hints and suggestions of things to come.

53:30.340 --> 53:32.220
I would personally appreciate it very much

53:32.220 --> 53:35.920
if you'd give us a call periodically and tell us what you found.

53:35.920 --> 53:39.040
It's too easy for us to go through here

53:39.040 --> 53:41.580
and at the end of a week or so walk off

53:41.580 --> 53:43.000
and never really know what happened

53:43.000 --> 53:45.040
and never know what kind of data came out.

53:46.160 --> 53:49.420
And I think that makes us very poor salesmen.

53:50.800 --> 53:53.280
I think you could help us do the job

53:53.280 --> 53:56.220
to kind of feed back the quality of the data that you've been getting

53:56.220 --> 53:57.880
if you could keep us informed.

53:58.300 --> 54:01.620
Please don't ever feel like you're interfering with our operation

54:01.620 --> 54:04.080
or don't be inhibited to call us.

54:04.660 --> 54:06.680
If we can't come to the phone and take the data

54:06.680 --> 54:07.980
or talk to you about it,

54:08.940 --> 54:11.440
the secretary will take the number and we'll be glad to call you back.

54:12.380 --> 54:15.440
And if there's any time when you have some question about the data,

54:15.600 --> 54:18.360
it doesn't matter how trivial it may seem to you.

54:18.740 --> 54:19.860
If you want to look at some data

54:19.860 --> 54:23.800
and you're curious to know whether we've ever seen a particular observation

54:23.800 --> 54:27.180
or whether the spacecraft was moving at the time your data was taken

54:27.180 --> 54:30.360
or I don't care how far out it might seem to you,

54:30.840 --> 54:32.160
questions are pretty cheap

54:32.160 --> 54:34.680
and not asking questions can be very expensive.

54:35.120 --> 54:37.920
And so please feel like our job isn't finished

54:37.920 --> 54:40.600
until you guys have all the information you can use.

54:41.240 --> 54:44.000
And I would like for you to feel like you can call any time.

54:44.440 --> 54:45.180
Thank you very much.

54:45.180 --> 54:49.080
I'd like to say, give you my thanks also.

54:49.440 --> 54:51.580
I was very pleased with the way all the gear worked,

54:52.020 --> 54:54.180
especially my part on the lunar surface

54:54.180 --> 54:56.840
and the part I saw of Ken in orbit.

54:58.300 --> 55:03.080
It was just a real pleasure to have him placed all this stuff for all you people

55:03.080 --> 55:05.020
and glad it's working so well.

55:06.100 --> 55:08.720
And thanks for the opportunity of going.

55:08.860 --> 55:12.220
If you can gin up another one, I'll be glad to go along again.

55:12.460 --> 55:12.920
Thank you.

55:15.180 --> 55:45.160
Thank you.

